ectual, corporeal, and spiritual capacities, which entitle them equally to essentially human prerogatives, and she displays her breadth of knowledge as she harnesses evidence from biblical, classical, patristic, and contemporary secular sources to bolster her claim. Forgotten over the centuries, these writings have been gaining increasing attention from feminist historians, students of philosophy, and scholars of seventeenth-century French literature and culture. This translation, from Domna C. Stanton and Rebecca M. Wilkin, marks the first time these works will appear in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCelibacyvEarly works to 1800. 0aCelibacyxEarly works to 1800. 0aPolitical ethicsvEarly works to 1800. 0aPolitical ethicsxEarly works to 1800. 0aWomenvEarly works to 1800. 0aWomenxEarly works to 1800. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aStanton, Domna C.1 aWilkin, Rebecca M.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226779232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226779232.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles